05844nam a22009855i 9780520340602DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203406027 a10.1525/97805203406022doi  a(DE-B1597)544246  a(OCoLC)1153486916  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aDC731b.G6313 1998 7aHIS0100002bisacsh04a944/.36104/0822201 aGodineau, Dominique, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Women of Paris and Their French Revolution /cDominique Godineau.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (440 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies on the History of Society and Culture ;v2600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface: Marianne's Hands -- tAbbreviations -- t1. PARISIAN LIFE IN THE FRENCH REVOLUTION -- t1. Passersby -- t2. Family Relations of Women of the People -- t3. Women at Work -- t2. ASPIRING CITIZENS -- t4. Birth of the Female Sansculottes Movement, 1789-1793 -- t5. Women as Guardians of the Nation -- t6. Light and Shadows, Summer 1793 -- t7. Citizenship Denied, Autumn 1793 -- t8. The Search for Basic Necessities, January-July 1794 -- t3. REVOLUTIONARY DAILY LIFE OF WOMEN OF THE PEOPLE -- t9. Political Culture and Female Sociability -- t10. Political Mentalité and Behavior of Women of the People -- t11. At the Margins of the Revolution -- t12. Sexual Difference and Equal Rights -- t4. A MASS WOMEN'S MOVEMENT -- t13. From the Militant Woman to Crowds of Women, November 1794-March 1795 -- t14. Firebrands, April-May 1795 -- t15. "Bread and the Constitution" -- t16. Women's Silence -- tConclusion -- tAppendix 1: Chronology of the Revolution -- tAppendix 2: Sections of Paris -- tAppendix 3: Portraits of Militant Women -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the French Revolution, hundreds of domestic and working-class women of Paris were interrogated, examined, accused, denounced, arrested, and imprisoned for their rebellious and often hostile behavior. Here, for the first time in English translation, Dominique Godineau offers an illuminating account of these female revolutionaries. As nurturing and tender as they are belligerent and contentious, these are not singular female heroines but the collective common women who struggled for bare subsistence by working in factories, in shops, on the streets, and on the home front while still finding time to participate in national assemblies, activist gatherings, and public demonstrations in their fight for the recognition of women as citizens within a burgeoning democracy. Relying on exhaustive research in historical archives, police accounts, and demographic resources at specific moments of the Revolutionary period, Godineau describes the private and public lives of these women within their precise political, social, historical, and gender-specific contexts. Her insightful and engaging observations shed new light on the importance of women as instigators, activists, militants, and decisive revolutionary individuals in the crafting and rechartering of their political and social roles as female citizens within the New Republic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aWomen in public lifezFrancezParisxHistoryy18th century. 0aWomenzFrancezParisxSocial conditions. 0aWorking class womenzFrancezParisxHistoryy18th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aactivism.  aactivists.  acitizenship.  ademocracy.  adomestic women.  aequal rights.  afamily relations.  afemale revolutionaries.  afemale sansculottes movement.  afeminism.  afrance.  afrench revolution.  agen